Species.or.unit.name: Anagallis arvensis
USDA puts in family Primulaceae and considers annual or biennial, but it does not appear to perennate at JRBP

Species.or.unit.name: Bromus commutatus
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Bromus japonicus, B. racemosus (?)
Taxonomy complicated and contradictory.

Species.or.unit.name: Briza maxima
First appeared in JRGCE plots in 2006

Species.or.unit.name: Bromus madritensis
First found in JRGCE in 2011 in plot 1-4

Species.or.unit.name: Taraxia ovata
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Camissonia ovata; Oenothera ovata
CalFlora does not specify or link directly to USDA name/code.

Species.or.unit.name: Cerastium glomeratum
First found in plot 11 in 2011 during species sort of H1.

Species.or.unit.name: Erigeron canadensis
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Conyza canadensis
USDA considers this annual/biennial; typically annual at JR.  CalFlora says that the equivalent USDA plant is Conyza canadensis var. canadensis (COCAC3)

Species.or.unit.name: Croton setigerus
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Eremocarpus setigerus
Found outside plots, sometimes in substantial numbers

Species.or.unit.name: CrepisËvesicaria ssp. taraxacifolia
can be annual, biennial, or perennial but lives >1 year at Jasper Ridge so treated as perennial.

Species.or.unit.name: Erodium botrys
USDA considers this annual/biennial; typically annual at JR.

Species.or.unit.name: Erodium cicutarium
First found in JRGCE in 2011 in plot 5-3. ; USDA considers this annual/biennial; typically annual at JR.

Species.or.unit.name: Geranium dissectum
USDA considers this annual/biennial;  typically annual at JR.

Species.or.unit.name: Genista monspessulana
Could be from seeds produced during experimental introductions in 2007-9, or could have dispersed in as invasives.

Species.or.unit.name: Kickxia spuria
USDA puts this in Scrophulariaceae.

Species.or.unit.name: Lactuca serriola
USDA considers this annual/biennial; ours don't perennate.

Species.or.unit.name: Lythrum hyssopifolia
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Lythrum hyssopifolium
USDA uses the masc ending for the species name: Lythrum hyssopifolium.  First identified in JRGCE in 2005, but likely found in 2004

Species.or.unit.name: Festuca perennis
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Lolium multiflorum
typically annual at JRGCE; CalFlora does not specify or link directly to USDA name/code.

Species.or.unit.name: Acmispon americanus var. americanus
Earlier.or.other.species.name: Lotus purshianus
CalFlora does not specify or link directly to USDA name/code.

Species.or.unit.name: Madia gracilis
First found in the plots in 2009

Species.or.unit.name: Medicago polymorpha
Until 2006 Trifolium dubium was mis-identified as this Medicago species, which is common at Jasper Ridge but most likely not within JRGCE.

Species.or.unit.name: Parentucellia viscosa
USDA puts this in Scrophulariaceae. Plants found along the boardwalk near Plot 7 and 8 and elsewhere in 2011. Nona thought that a seedling found in plot 7-1 was this species, but it was dead by the time late speceis survey was conducted, so it could not be verified.

Species.or.unit.name: Senecio vulgaris
Found first in 2011 in Plot 7-4. USDA considers annual or biennial.

Species.or.unit.name: Trifolium dubium
This species may have been mis-identified as Medicago polymorpha until 2006.

Species.or.unit.name: Trifolium subterraneum
First identified in 2007.

Species.or.unit.name: Apiaceae, unidentified
If identified only to family, then most likely too small to be flowering, and therefore the whole plant would have been taken.

Species.or.unit.name: Asteraceae, unidentified
If identified only to family, then most likely too small to be flowering, and therefore the whole plant would have been taken.

Species.or.unit.name: Brassicaceae, unidentified
If identified only to family, then most likely too small to be flowering, and therefore the whole plant would have been taken.

Species.or.unit.name: Euphorbia
ours are small, likely annual

Species.or.unit.name: forb, annual, unidentified
Unknown forbs usually are very small, and stored in annual plant bags.

Species.or.unit.name: Galium (not G. murale)
Except for G. murale (the tiny Galium), the other four Galiums at JR are native.

Species.or.unit.name: Lupinus
Probably either Lupinus bicolor or Lupinus nanus. Rarely found.

Species.or.unit.name: unidentified senesced annual grass
in some years, lumped with UNSEN

Species.or.unit.name: Urospermum picroides
It is likely this is the species started showing up (or getting recognized) in 2008 first in Pl2Q3

Species.or.unit.name: Vicia tetrasperma
A big patch of this species existed in between Plot 5 and 6 in 2006.
